  <!-- EXAM-STYLE MIXED PROBLEMS                              -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <paragraphs xml:id="par-circle-mixed-intro">
    <title>Exam-Style Mixed Problems</title>

    <p>These problems combine multiple skills, just like the real
    exam. Attempt each one fully before checking the answer.
    Use Pólya's four steps on every question.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-1">
    <title>Mixed Problem 1</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A circle has centre <m>(1, -2)</m> and passes through
      the point <m>(4, 2)</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Find the radius.</p>
      <p>(b) Write the equation of the circle.</p>
      <p>(c) Investigate whether <m>(6, -2)</m> is on, inside, or
      outside the circle.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) <m>r = \sqrt{(4-1)^2+(2-(-2))^2} = \sqrt{9+16}
      = 5</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) <m>(x-1)^2 + (y+2)^2 = 25</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) <m>(6-1)^2 + (-2+2)^2 = 25 = r^2</m> → ON the
      circle.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-2">
    <title>Mixed Problem 2</title>
    <statement>
      <p>The circle <m>k</m> has equation
      <m>(x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 = 36</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Write down the centre and radius.</p>
      <p>(b) Write down the coordinates of the highest and lowest
      points on <m>k</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) Is the point <m>(1, 1)</m> inside or outside
      <m>k</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) Centre <m>(-2, 5)</m>, radius 6.</p>
      <p>(b) Highest: <m>(-2, 5+6) = (-2, 11)</m>. Lowest:
      <m>(-2, 5-6) = (-2, -1)</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) <m>(1+2)^2 + (1-5)^2 = 9+16 = 25 &lt; 36</m> →
      INSIDE.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-3">
    <title>Mixed Problem 3</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A circle has its centre on the positive x-axis and is
      tangent to both the x-axis and the line <m>y = 8</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Find the radius and the y-coordinate of the centre.</p>
      <p>(b) The point <m>(-3, 4)</m> is on the circle. Find the
      x-coordinate of the centre and write the equation.</p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>(a) If tangent to <m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 8</m>, the
      centre must be halfway between them.</p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) Centre is midway between <m>y = 0</m> and
      <m>y = 8</m>, so <m>k = 4</m> and <m>r = 4</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) Centre is <m>(h, 4)</m>. Substitute
      <m>(-3, 4)</m>: <m>(-3 - h)^2 + (4 - 4)^2 = 16</m>,
      so <m>(-3 - h)^2 = 16</m>, giving <m>-3 - h = \pm 4</m>.
      Since centre is on the positive x-axis: <m>h = 1</m>.
      Equation: <m>(x - 1)^2 + (y - 4)^2 = 16</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-4">
    <title>Mixed Problem 4</title>
    <statement>
      <p>The circle <m>c</m> has centre <m>(3, 4)</m> and
      passes through the origin <m>(0, 0)</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Find the radius.</p>
      <p>(b) Write the equation of <m>c</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) Write down the coordinates of the point on <m>c</m>
      that is furthest from the origin.</p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>(c) The furthest point from the origin is on the far side
      of the circle from <m>(0, 0)</m>, along the line through the
      origin and the centre.</p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) <m>r = \sqrt{(3-0)^2 + (4-0)^2} = \sqrt{9+16}
      = 5</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) <m>(x-3)^2 + (y-4)^2 = 25</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) Furthest point is diametrically opposite the origin
      through the centre: <m>(6, 8)</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-5">
    <title>Mixed Problem 5 (Challenge)</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A circle passes through the points <m>A(0, 0)</m>,
      <m>B(6, 0)</m>, and <m>C(0, 8)</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Find the midpoint of <m>[BC]</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) Show that the centre of the circle is the midpoint
      of <m>[BC]</m>.</p>
      <p>(c) Find the radius and write the equation of the
      circle.</p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>What type of triangle is <m>ABC</m>? What theorem tells
      you about the circumscribed circle of a right-angled
      triangle?</p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) Midpoint of <m>BC</m> = <m>(3, 4)</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) Triangle <m>ABC</m> is right-angled at <m>A</m>
      (check: <m>|AB|^2 + |AC|^2 = 36 + 64 = 100 = |BC|^2</m>).
      For a right-angled triangle, the circumcentre is the
      midpoint of the hypotenuse.</p>
      <p>(c) <m>r = \frac{|BC|}{2} = 5</m>. Centre
      <m>(3, 4)</m>. Equation:
      <m>(x-3)^2 + (y-4)^2 = 25</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-circle-mixed-6">
    <title>Mixed Problem 6 (Challenge)</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Two circles have equations
      <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m> and
      <m>(x - 7)^2 + y^2 = 9</m>.</p>
      <p>(a) Write down the centre and radius of each circle.</p>
      <p>(b) Find the distance between the centres.</p>
      <p>(c) Do the circles overlap, touch, or are they
      separate? Explain your reasoning.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>(a) Circle 1: centre <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>r_1 = 5</m>.
      Circle 2: centre <m>(7,0)</m>, <m>r_2 = 3</m>.</p>
      <p>(b) Distance = 7.</p>
      <p>(c) <m>r_1 + r_2 = 5 + 3 = 8 > 7</m>, so the circles
      overlap (two intersection points). If the distance equalled
      <m>r_1 + r_2</m> they would touch externally.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

